      <hedline>
        <hl1>Being There, Or Nearly So</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>David Rowland letter notes one technique used by a friend to deal with a man in an elevator making a loud, self-important cell phone call (June 22 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Cell Phone Feedback'' (Incoming, June 22), about the rude behavior often seen in public places by people using cell phones:</p>
        <p>A friend of mine who is a musician found himself in an elevator with a man making a loud, self-important call. My friend started singing.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Cell Phone Feedback'' (Incoming, June 22), about the rude behavior often seen in public places by people using cell phones:</p>
        <p>A friend of mine who is a musician found himself in an elevator with a man making a loud, self-important call. My friend started singing.</p>
        <p>The caller glared at him and said, ''Excuse me, but this is a business call.'' My friend replied, ''I'm a professional songwriter -- this is a business song.''</p>
        <p>DAVID ROWLAND  Berkeley, Calif.</p>
      </block>
